I"<p>If one views <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attention-is-a-competition">attention</a> as <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attention-is-representational-resource-allocation">a process of representational resource allocation</a>, then <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/binding-problem-can-be-divided-into-several-subproblems">attentional binding</a> can be seen as the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neuroplasticity-is-like-protein-folding">integrative increase in coherence following pressure</a>. When attending to aspects of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/representationism-in-cognition-is-adaptationism-in-evolution">the world</a> or to thoughts or <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/consciousness-contains-transient-latent-representations">raw sensations</a>, the coherence necessity of internal representation, coupled with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attention-is-representational-resource-allocation">significant representational resources being allocated to that object</a> result in a deep integration. This integrative coherence might be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/glom-enables-hierarchical-representations-in-continuous-spaces">neurally realized through an architecture like GLOM</a>.</p>
